#compdef bcrypter
# ============================================================================
# bcrypter - stdin-to-stdout bcrypt password hasher
#             (Go, source-available)
#
# Author : Kai (kai5263499)
# Upstream: https://github.com/kai5263499/bcrypter
#
# `bcrypter` is a minimal Go CLI that reads a single
# line of password text from stdin, runs it through
# `bcrypt.GenerateFromPassword` at the library's
# default cost factor (10), and writes the resulting
# $2a$ MCF-formatted hash to stdout.
#
# Usage:
#   echo "hunter2" | bcrypter
#   read -s -p "Password: " pw && echo -n "$pw" \
#       | bcrypter
#
# No flags. The CLI is deliberately minimal - the
# input is one line of password text from stdin,
# the output is one line containing the bcrypt hash.
# Cost factor is the bcrypt library's default
# (`bcrypt.DefaultCost` = 10), which is the OWASP
# 2024 recommendation for new code.
#
# The golang.org/x/crypto/bcrypt lane is built on the
# Go core team's bcrypt implementation in the
# `golang.org/x/crypto` subrepository, the canonical
# Go bcrypt library. The implementation tracks
# Provos + Mazières's 1999 USENIX paper "A Future-
# Adaptable Password Scheme" + the OpenBSD reference
# C implementation in `pwd_mkdb.c`.
#
# The library lives at `golang.org/x/crypto/bcrypt`
# rather than the std-lib `crypto/bcrypt` because the
# Go core team's policy distinguishes between
# *primitive* crypto algorithms (placed in std-lib
# `crypto/*` once stable + widely-used: sha1, sha256,
# aes, rsa, ed25519, ...) and *higher-level* crypto
# functions like password hashing + key derivation
# (placed in the `golang.org/x/crypto` subrepo:
# bcrypt, scrypt, argon2, pbkdf2, ...).
#
# The bcrypt-specific reason for the subrepo placement
# is treated by the Go core team as "stable but
# legacy" - Argon2 (Axis 244) is the recommended
# password-hashing algorithm for new code (per OWASP
# 2024 + RFC 9106), and bcrypt is maintained at
# x/crypto for backward compatibility with deployed
# systems where the migration cost isn't justified.
# Compare ed25519 (Axis 246) which was promoted from
# x/crypto/ed25519 to std-lib crypto/ed25519 in Go
# 1.13 (September 2019) because Ed25519 is the
# *forward-recommended* primitive, not a legacy one.
#
# golang.org/x/crypto/bcrypt is depended on by:
#   - Caddy (admin API password hashing)
#   - Gitea (user account password storage)
#   - Drone (CI/CD admin authentication)
#   - GoTrue + Supabase Auth (account password hashing)
#   - Hugo (admin server bcrypt verification)
#   - bcrypter (THIS BINARY)
#
# bcrypter uses `bcrypt.GenerateFromPassword(pw,
# bcrypt.DefaultCost)` for hash generation - the
# DefaultCost constant is 10 (matching OpenBSD's
# default + OWASP's 2024 recommendation for new code).
# At cost 10 the hash function takes ~100ms per
# computation on modern hardware, which is the
# OWASP-recommended baseline for password-storage
# attack resistance.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 254 :: bcrypt password hashing (Provos +
#              Mazières 1999, OpenBSD origin;
#              adaptive cost factor)
# Round 1461 :: Go slot 2 of 4 :: continues Axis 254
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : Keats/rust-bcrypt           [R1460 _floundr]
#   Go      : golang.org/x/crypto/bcrypt  [R1461 THIS FILE]
#             (core-team subrepo)
#   TS/Node : kelektiv/node.bcrypt.js     [R1462 closing]
#
# golang.org/x/crypto/bcrypt is structurally
# interesting in this axis because of its *stayed-at-
# x/crypto-not-promoted-to-std-lib* policy decision.
# The three lanes form a clean spectrum:
#
#   - Rust (Keats/rust-bcrypt): single-author
#     canonical impl by Vincent Prouillet; part of
#     Keats's two-axis canonical position (bcrypt +
#     jsonwebtoken at Axis 241)
#   - Go (x/crypto/bcrypt): Go core team
#     implementation in subrepo; intentionally
#     stayed at x/crypto rather than promoting to
#     std-lib because bcrypt is treated as "stable
#     but legacy" - Argon2 is recommended for new
#     code
#   - Node (kelektiv/node.bcrypt.js): native N-API
#     binding to OpenBSD's reference C
#     implementation; ~3M weekly downloads
#
# The Go subrepo placement decision is policy-
# differentiated from earlier axes:
#   - Ed25519 (Axis 246): promoted from x/crypto to
#     std-lib in Go 1.13 (forward-recommended)
#   - Argon2 (Axis 244): stays at x/crypto/argon2
#     (forward-recommended but still adoption-
#     evolving, treated like x/* by design)
#   - bcrypt (Axis 254, THIS AXIS): stays at
#     x/crypto/bcrypt (legacy-maintained, not
#     forward-recommended)
#
# This three-way policy distinction is unique to the
# Go ecosystem - Rust + Node don't have an equivalent
# "stdlib promotion" mechanism for crypto primitives,
# so library placement is governed by package-
# manager conventions rather than canonical-team
# policy decisions.
#
# Cross-language interop at the wire format level - a
# bcrypt $2a$ / $2b$ hash produced by rust-bcrypt +
# x/crypto/bcrypt + kelektiv/node.bcrypt.js + the
# OpenBSD reference C implementation verifies byte-
# identically across all canonical implementations.
# ============================================================================

_bcrypter() {
    # No flags - stdin to stdout password hasher
    _arguments
}

_bcrypter "$@"
